body: Essentially a version of PyDict_Next that returns on owned reference for keys/values. On platforms with CYTHON_AVOID_BORROWED_REFS it doesn't ever go through a borrowed reference which I think should help because it reduces the amount of objects that are ambiguous if they can be cleaned up.

comment_data.body: I don't think these lengthy and unwieldy names make the C code easier to read. My gut feeling is that it would be clearer with explicit `#if  CYTHON_AVOID_BORROWED_REFS` sections that line up with the remaining injected code, e.g. the decref below in this function.
I don't think this needs to be repeated. It should be enough to make it part of the prototype declaration.
comment_data.diff_hunk:
@@ -3388,3 +3391,104 @@ static PyObject *__Pyx_PyList_Pack(Py_ssize_t n, ...) {
 #else
 #define __Pyx_PyObject_LengthHint(o, defaultval)  PyObject_LengthHint(o, defaultval)
 #endif
+
+//////////////////////// OwnedDictNext.proto ///////////////////////////////
+
+#if CYTHON_AVOID_BORROWED_REFS
+#define __PYX_PYDICT_NEXTREF_PPOS PyObject*
+#define __PYX_XDECREF_PYDICT_NEXTREF_PPOS(ppos) Py_XDECREF(ppos)
+#else
+#define __PYX_PYDICT_NEXTREF_PPOS Py_ssize_t
+#define __PYX_XDECREF_PYDICT_NEXTREF_PPOS(ppos)
+#endif
+
+// Like PyDict_Next but pkey and pvalue are new references (and thus must be decrefed).
+// pkey and pvalue may be NULL but this must be the same for all subsequent calls.
+// If it encounters an exception it prints it as unraisable and stops.
+#if !CYTHON_AVOID_BORROWED_REFS
+CYTHON_INLINE
+#endif
+static int __Pyx_PyDict_NextRef(PyObject *p, __PYX_PYDICT_NEXTREF_PPOS *ppos, PyObject **pkey, PyObject **pvalue); /* proto */
+
+//////////////////////// OwnedDictNext //////////////////////////////////////
+//@requires: Builtins.c::py_dict_values
+//@requires: Builtins.c::py_dict_items
+
+#if !CYTHON_AVOID_BORROWED_REFS
+CYTHON_INLINE
+#endif

comment_data.body:
Just to mention it, it's funny to see this guarded section do an incref after the fact, which does obviously not match the intention of its guard. :)

`__Pyx_PyDict_NextRef()` has a somewhat costly implementation, though, so the reasons to use it should be well chosen. In theory, `CYTHON_AVOID_THREAD_UNSAFE_BORROWED_REFS` seems such a reason – in practice, maybe.
Did you miss this bit or was it intentional?
I think these don't need special macros either. They seem just fine with macro guards.

Yeah this is definitely intentional. The surrounding critical section is enough to make the gap between `PyDict_Next` and the `INCREF` safe, but we don't want to do anything complicated without an incref (because critical sections are easily interrupted).

I'll add a comment though.
Actually it probably makes sense to use `__Pyx_PyDict_NextRef` instead here. I'll use the relatively cheap "incref after the fact" implementation so it's pretty much equivalent.

commit.message:
Add __Pyx_PyDict_NextRef (and related functions)

Essentially a version of PyDict_Next that returns on owned
reference for keys/values. On platforms with CYTHON_AVOID_BORROWED_REFS
it doesn't ever go through a borrowed reference which I think
should help because it reduces the amount of objects that are
ambiguous if they can be cleaned up.
